statement:
Consider the following problem involving Laplace's equation in an
annular region:

\begin{align*}u_{rr} + \frac1{r} u_r + \frac1{r^2}u_{\theta \theta} = 0,  \quad 1 < r < 2, \quad 0 < \theta < \pi/2.\end{align*}

\begin{align*}u(1,\theta) = 0, \quad u(2,\theta) = 0, \quad u(r,0) = 0, \quad u(r,\pi/2) = f(r).\end{align*}

Find the solution for a general function $f(r)$.

sols:
In
\href{Science:Math_Exam_Resources/Courses/MATH257/December_2011/Question_5_(a)}{part
(a)} we found a solution for a specific f(r) that happened to be one of
the original eigenfunctions and so we were able to compare just by
analyzing the coefficient of one term. However now we have a general
f(r) and if we continue from
\href{Science:Math_Exam_Resources/Courses/MATH257/December_2011/Question_5_(a)}{part
(a)} we have,

\begin{align*}u\left(r,\frac{\pi}{2}\right)=\sum_{n=1}^\infty B_n \sin\left(\frac{n \pi}{\ln(2)} \ln(r)\right) \sinh\left(\lambda_n \frac{\pi}{2}\right) = f(r).\end{align*}

We wish to impose an orthogonality argument so that we can isolate each
individual coefficient, $B_n$. Recall that if we have a problem in
Sturm-Liouville form,

\begin{align*}\frac{\textrm{d}}{\textrm{d}r}\left(p(r)\frac{\textrm{d}\psi}{\textrm{d}r}\right)-q(r)\psi+\sigma(r)\mu\psi=0\end{align*}

then the eigenfunctions $\psi$ have the orthogonality relationship

\begin{align*}\int_a^b\psi_n\psi_m\sigma(r)\textrm{d}r=0,\quad{}n\neq{m}.\end{align*}

Our eigenfunction problem for r was

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}r^2 R'' + r R' + \left(\frac{n\pi}{\ln{2}} \right)^2 R = 0\end{align*}

which we can write in Sturm-Liouville form to get

\begin{align*}\frac{\textrm{d}}{\textrm{d}r}\left(r\frac{\textrm{d}R}{\textrm{d}r}\right)+\frac{1}{{\color{blue} r}} \left(\frac{n\pi}{\ln{2}} \right)^2 R=0\end{align*}

so our orthogonality relation is

\begin{align*}
&\int_a^b\frac{R_nR_m}{{\color{blue} r}}\textrm{d}r\\&=\int_1^2\sin\left(\frac{n\pi}{\ln{2}}\ln{r}\right)\sin\left(\frac{m\pi}{\ln{2}}\ln{r}\right)\frac{1}{r}\textrm{d}r\end{align*}

If we compute the integrals we can use a substitution of

\begin{align*}
x&=\frac{\ln{r}}{\ln{2}}\\
\textrm{d}x&=\frac{1}{\ln{2}}\frac{1}{r}\textrm{d}r\end{align*}

to get

\begin{align*}\ln{2}\int_0^1\sin\left(n\pi{x}\right)\sin\left(m\pi{x}\right)\textrm{d}x.\end{align*}

We immediately recognize this new integral as the standard sine
orthogonality relation and so we get

\begin{align*}
&\int_1^2\sin\left(\frac{n\pi}{\ln{2}}\ln{r}\right)\sin\left(\frac{m\pi}{\ln{2}}\ln{r}\right)\frac{1}{r}\textrm{d}r\\
&=\ln{2}\int_0^1\sin\left(n\pi{x}\right)\sin\left(m\pi{x}\right)\textrm{d}x=
\begin{cases}
0&, n\neq{m}\\
\frac{\ln{2}}{2}&, n=m
\end{cases}.\end{align*}

Returning to

\begin{align*}\sum_{n=1}^\infty B_n \sin\left(\frac{n \pi}{\ln(2)} \ln(r)\right) \sinh\left(\lambda_n \frac{\pi}{2}\right) = f(r)\end{align*}

we can use our orthogonality relation to get

\begin{align*}
&B_n\sinh\left(\lambda_n \frac{\pi}{2}\right)\frac{\ln{2}}{2}=\int_1^2f(r)\sin\left(\frac{n \pi}{\ln(2)} \ln(r)\right)\frac{1}{r}\textrm{d}r\\
&B_n=\frac{2}{\ln{2}}\frac{1}{\sinh\left(\lambda_n \frac{\pi}{2}\right)}\int_1^2f(r)\sin\left(\frac{n \pi}{\ln(2)} \ln(r)\right)\frac{1}{r}\textrm{d}r.\end{align*}

Therefore we now have the constants $B_m$ for any $f(r)$ and therefore
we have the solution to the partial differential equation,

\begin{align*}u(r,\theta)=  \sum_{n=1}^\infty B_n \sin\left(\frac{n \pi}{\ln(2)} \ln(r)\right) \sinh\left(\lambda_n \theta\right).\end{align*}
